Thats a great question the best health care datasets depend somewhat on what kinds of analysis you want to do (costs, utilization, outcomes, access, epidemiology, etc.), but there are several high-value, publicly available health datasets on Data.gov (or HealthData.gov) that are excellent for learning, exploration, and serious research. Below are some strong options + tips, and then some advice on choosing one to work with.

1. High-value health datasets on Data.gov / HealthData.gov

Here are some of the most useful and interesting datasets you might consider:

2. Advice for selecting a dataset

To pick one (or a few) that are best for your analysis, consider:

  • Scope / Level: Do you want national, state, county, facility, or individual (micro) level?

  • Access restrictions: Some datasets (especially HCUP large inpatient files) require you to apply or pay; others are fully public.

  • Completeness / missingness / quality: Some will have many missing variables or restricted variables; check data dictionaries and documentation.

  • Time span / trend potential: If you want to model time trends, pick a dataset that spans many years.

  • Richness / number of variables: More variables allow more flexible modeling (demographics, comorbidities, costs, outcomes, etc.).

  • Feasibility / size: Extremely large datasets may require more computational resources.

3. Suggested best for learning / analysis picks

If I were choosing a dataset to start with, I might pick:

  • MEPS (Medical Expenditure Panel Survey) because it gives you detailed individual / household level data on health use, costs, insurance, etc.

  • National Survey on Drug Use and Health (NSDUH) good for behavioral / mental health modeling.

  • Leading Causes of Death / Mortality datasets to practice epidemiologic / trend modeling.

  • HCUP public use files (e.g. NIS public use file) to get exposure to hospital data, but without requiring full restricted access.

Lets assume your file is called drug_deaths.csv.

python
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv("drug_deaths.csv")

# Quick peek
print(df.head())
print(df.info())

# 1. Clean column names
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip().str.lower().str.replace(" ", "_")

# 2. Handle missing values (example: fill or drop)
df = df.dropna(subset=["year", "deaths"])

# 3. Basic yearly trend
yearly = df.groupby("year")["deaths"].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.lineplot(data=yearly, x="year", y="deaths", marker="o")
plt.title("Accidental Drug Deaths Over Time")
plt.ylabel("Total Deaths")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.show()

# 4. Deaths by substance type
if "substance" in df.columns:
    substance = df.groupby("substance")["deaths"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).head(10)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.barplot(x=substance.values, y=substance.index)
    plt.title("Top 10 Substances Involved in Deaths")
    plt.xlabel("Total Deaths")
    plt.ylabel("Substance")
    plt.show()

This gives you:

Python Script: Clean & Export for Tableau

python
import pandas as pd

# Step 1: Load the raw dataset
df = pd.read_csv("drug_deaths_raw.csv")

# Step 2: Standardize column names
df.columns = (
    df.columns.str.strip()
              .str.lower()
              .str.replace(" ", "_")
              .str.replace(r"[^\w\s]", "", regex=True)
)

# Step 3: Inspect data
print(df.head())
print(df.info())
print(df.isnull().sum())

# Step 4: Handle missing values
# Example: drop rows with missing deaths or year
df = df.dropna(subset=["year", "deaths"])

# Optionally fill missing values in categorical columns
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include="object").columns
for col in categorical_cols:
    df[col] = df[col].fillna("Unknown")

# Step 5: Fix data types
df["year"] = df["year"].astype(int)
df["deaths"] = pd.to_numeric(df["deaths"], errors="coerce")

# Example: if you have a date column
if "date" in df.columns:
    df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"], errors="coerce")

# Step 6: Feature engineering (optional)
# Create age groups
if "age" in df.columns:
    bins = [0, 18, 35, 50, 65, 120]
    labels = ["0-17", "18-34", "35-49", "50-64", "65+"]
    df["age_group"] = pd.cut(df["age"], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

# Step 7: Save cleaned dataset for Tableau
df.to_csv("drug_deaths_cleaned.csv", index=False)

print(" Cleaned dataset saved as drug_deaths_cleaned.csv")

You said:
What can I use to forecast overdose deaths
ChatGPT said:

Great question forecasting overdose deaths is a time series problem, and you have multiple options in Python depending on how sophisticated you want to go.

Forecasting Approaches

1. Simple Statistical Models

  • ARIMA / SARIMA (AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average)

    • Good for structured, stationary time series (e.g., yearly or monthly deaths).

    • Handles trends and seasonality if tuned properly.

  • Exponential Smoothing (Holt-Winters)

    • Great if you suspect seasonality and long-term trend.

Packages: statsmodels

2. Modern Time-Series Forecasting

  • Facebook Prophet (now called prophet)

    • Very user-friendly, handles seasonality, trends, holidays.

    • Works well with messy real-world health data.

Package: prophet

3. Machine Learning Models

  • Random Forests / Gradient Boosted Trees (XGBoost, LightGBM)

    • You treat time as a feature and predict deaths.

    • Good if you add explanatory variables (like unemployment rate, fentanyl seizure data, naloxone distribution).

  • Neural Networks (LSTM, GRU, Transformer)

    • Powerful for sequential dependencies.

    • Overkill unless you have lots of data.

Packages: scikit-learn, xgboost, pytorch, tensorflow

Example: Forecasting with Prophet

Lets assume you have monthly overdose deaths in columns: date, deaths.

python
import pandas as pd
from prophet import Prophet
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load your cleaned data
df = pd.read_csv("drug_deaths_cleaned.csv")

# Make sure 'date' is datetime
df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"])

# Prophet needs columns 'ds' (date) and 'y' (value)
data = df.groupby("date")["deaths"].sum().reset_index()
data = data.rename(columns={"date": "ds", "deaths": "y"})

# Build and fit model
model = Prophet(yearly_seasonality=True, weekly_seasonality=False, daily_seasonality=False)
model.fit(data)

# Forecast 24 months into the future
future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=24, freq="M")
forecast = model.predict(future)

# Plot results
fig1 = model.plot(forecast)
plt.title("Forecasted Overdose Deaths")
plt.show()

fig2 = model.plot_components(forecast)
plt.show()

When to Use What

  • Prophet if you want quick, interpretable forecasts (best starting point).

  • ARIMA/SARIMA if your data is clean and you want statistical rigor.

  • ML (XGBoost, LSTM) if you have extra predictors (economic data, prescriptions, fentanyl supply).

Python Pipeline (Clean Forecast Export for Tableau)

python
import pandas as pd
from prophet import Prophet

# ---------------------------
# STEP 1: Load & Clean Data
# ---------------------------
df = pd.read_csv("drug_deaths_raw.csv")

# Standardize column names
df.columns = (
    df.columns.str.strip()
              .str.lower()
              .str.replace(" ", "_")
              .str.replace(r"[^\w\s]", "", regex=True)
)

# Assume dataset has 'date' and 'deaths' columns
df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"], errors="coerce")
df = df.dropna(subset=["date", "deaths"])
df["deaths"] = pd.to_numeric(df["deaths"], errors="coerce")

# Aggregate by month (if daily data)
df = df.groupby(pd.Grouper(key="date", freq="M"))["deaths"].sum().reset_index()

# ---------------------------
# STEP 2: Prepare for Forecasting
# ---------------------------
data = df.rename(columns={"date": "ds", "deaths": "y"})

# Build Prophet model
model = Prophet(yearly_seasonality=True, weekly_seasonality=False, daily_seasonality=False)
model.fit(data)

# ---------------------------
# STEP 3: Forecast Future Deaths
# ---------------------------
future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=24, freq="M")  # forecast 24 months ahead
forecast = model.predict(future)

# ---------------------------
# STEP 4: Merge Historical + Forecast
# ---------------------------
# Keep only relevant columns
forecast_df = forecast[["ds", "yhat", "yhat_lower", "yhat_upper"]]

# Merge actuals and predictions
merged = pd.merge(data, forecast_df, on="ds", how="outer")

# Add a flag column for Tableau (Actual vs Forecast)
merged["type"] = merged["y"].notnull().map(lambda x: "Actual" if x else "Forecast")

# Rename for Tableau-friendly schema
final = merged.rename(columns={
    "ds": "date",
    "y": "deaths_actual",
    "yhat": "deaths_forecast",
    "yhat_lower": "forecast_lower",
    "yhat_upper": "forecast_upper"
})

# ---------------------------
# STEP 5: Export to CSV
# ---------------------------
final.to_csv("drug_deaths_forecast.csv", index=False)
print(" Cleaned + Forecasted dataset saved as drug_deaths_forecast.csv")

Python + Snowflake Code Example

Youll need the Snowflake Python Connector (snowflake-connector-python) and optionally SQLAlchemy if you like pandas integration.

python
import pandas as pd
from prophet import Prophet
import snowflake.connector

# ---------------------------
# STEP 1: Load & Clean Data
# ---------------------------
df = pd.read_csv("drug_deaths_raw.csv")
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip().str.lower().str.replace(" ", "_")
df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"], errors="coerce")
df = df.dropna(subset=["date", "deaths"])
df["deaths"] = pd.to_numeric(df["deaths"], errors="coerce")
df = df.groupby(pd.Grouper(key="date", freq="M"))["deaths"].sum().reset_index()

# ---------------------------
# STEP 2: Forecast with Prophet
# ---------------------------
data = df.rename(columns={"date": "ds", "deaths": "y"})
model = Prophet(yearly_seasonality=True)
model.fit(data)
future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=24, freq="M")
forecast = model.predict(future)

# ---------------------------
# STEP 3: Merge Results
# ---------------------------
forecast_df = forecast[["ds", "yhat", "yhat_lower", "yhat_upper"]]
merged = pd.merge(data, forecast_df, on="ds", how="outer")
merged["type"] = merged["y"].notnull().map(lambda x: "Actual" if x else "Forecast")

final = merged.rename(columns={
    "ds": "date",
    "y": "deaths_actual",
    "yhat": "deaths_forecast",
    "yhat_lower": "forecast_lower",
    "yhat_upper": "forecast_upper"
})

# ---------------------------
# STEP 4: Push to Snowflake
# ---------------------------
# Connection details (replace with yours or use env vars/Secrets Manager)
conn = snowflake.connector.connect(
    user="YOUR_USERNAME",
    password="YOUR_PASSWORD",
    account="YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID",    # e.g. abcd-xy12345
    warehouse="YOUR_WAREHOUSE",
    database="YOUR_DATABASE",
    schema="PUBLIC"
)

cur = conn.cursor()

# Create table if not exists
cur.execute("""
CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE DRUG_OVERDOSE_FORECAST (
    DATE DATE,
    DEATHS_ACTUAL FLOAT,
    DEATHS_FORECAST FLOAT,
    FORECAST_LOWER FLOAT,
    FORECAST_UPPER FLOAT,
    TYPE STRING
)
""")

# Use pandas to push data
success, nchunks, nrows, _ = cur.execute(
    "PUT file://drug_deaths_forecast.csv @%DRUG_OVERDOSE_FORECAST"
), 0, 0, None

# Alternative: write directly with pandas.to_sql via sqlalchemy-snowflake
# final.to_sql("DRUG_OVERDOSE_FORECAST", engine, if_exists="replace", index=False)

cur.close()
conn.close()

what does this do print(df_cleaned.columns.str.lower(inplace=True))
ChatGPT said:

Good catch Lets break it down:

python
print(df_cleaned.columns.str.lower(inplace=True))

1. df_cleaned.columns

This is an Index object containing all your column names.
Example:

python
Index(['Date', 'Deaths', 'Substance'], dtype='object')

2. .str.lower()

This applies .lower() to each column name (vectorized string operation).
Example:

python
Index(['date', 'deaths', 'substance'], dtype='object')

3. inplace=True

Heres the problem: .str.lower() does NOT support inplace=True.

  • inplace=True is used with methods like df.rename(), df.drop(), etc.

  • With .str.lower(), it simply raises an error or is ignored depending on your pandas version.

4. print(...)

  • If it did run, it would print the new lowercased column names as an Index.

  • But since inplace=True is invalid here, this line will either error out or just ignore inplace and return the transformed index.

Correct way to lowercase columns is:

python
df_cleaned.columns = df_cleaned.columns.str.lower()
print(df_cleaned.columns)

The drugs columns have two data inputs Y and empty. the empty values are N How do I resolve this
ChatGPT said:

Got it so your drug indicator columns (like heroin, fentanyl, etc.) have values like:

  • "Y" Yes (drug present)

  • "" (empty string) should really be "N" (No)

How to Fix in Pandas

You can replace empty strings with "N" and leave "Y" as is:

python
# Replace empty strings with "N" across all columns
df = df.replace("", "N")

# Or only for specific drug columns
drug_cols = ["heroin", "fentanyl", "cocaine"]
df[drug_cols] = df[drug_cols].replace("", "N")

Extra Improvement: Convert to Boolean

Sometimes its cleaner for analysis to convert "Y"/"N" into True/False (or 1/0):

python
# Map Y -> 1, N -> 0
df[drug_cols] = df[drug_cols].replace({"Y": 1, "N": 0})

This way you can do things like:

python
# Count how many deaths involved fentanyl
df["fentanyl"].sum()

# Count how many deaths involved multiple drugs
df["num_drugs"] = df[drug_cols].sum(axis=1)

This step will make forecasting + Tableau dashboards easier, because youll have clean binary values (instead of mixed blanks).

explain this df.columns = ( df.columns.str.strip() .str.lower() .str.replace(" ", "_") .str.replace(r"[^\w\s]", "", regex=True)
ChatGPT said:

Nice thats a column-cleaning pipeline youre looking at
Lets unpack it step by step:

python
df.columns = (
    df.columns.str.strip()                  # 1
              .str.lower()                  # 2
              .str.replace(" ", "_")        # 3
              .str.replace(r"[^\w\s]", "", regex=True)  # 4

1. .str.strip()

Removes leading/trailing spaces from column names.

python
" Death "  "Death"

2. .str.lower()

Converts everything to lowercase.

python
"Death Cause"  "death cause"

3. .str.replace(" ", "_")

Replaces spaces with underscores (so column names are valid for SQL, Tableau, Python).

python
"death cause"  "death_cause"

4. .str.replace(r"[^\w\s]", "", regex=True)

Removes any characters that are not letters, numbers, underscores, or spaces.

  • r"[^\w\s]" = anything that is NOT a word character (\w) or whitespace (\s)

  • ^ inside [] means NOT.

Examples:

python
"death (cause)?"  "death cause"
"drug-type#1"    "drugtype1"

Final Effect

This ensures your dataframe column names are:

  • Trimmed (no extra spaces)

  • Lowercase (consistent)

  • Snake_case (underscores instead of spaces)

  • Clean (no special characters like ?, -, ())

Result: You get column names that are Python, SQL, Snowflake, and Tableau friendly.

Great question lets break this down:

python
df["coords"] = df["residencecitygeo"].str.extract(r"\((.*?)\)")

1. df["residencecitygeo"].str.extract(...)

  • .str.extract(pattern) lets you pull out part of a string using regex.

  • It returns a new Series (or DataFrame if multiple groups).

2. The regex: r"\((.*?)\)"

  • \( match a literal opening parenthesis (

  • (.*?) capture everything inside the parentheses

    • . means any character

    • * means zero or more

    • ? makes it non-greedy (stop at the first ))

  • \) match a literal closing parenthesis )

So this pattern means:
Find text between parentheses.

df[["latitude", "longitude"]] (with double brackets)

  • This means: select multiple columns as a DataFrame.

  • You pass in a list of column names.

Example:

python

Returns a DataFrame with 2 columns.

nginx
   latitude   longitude
0  41.179195 -73.189476
1  41.554261 -73.043069

df["latitude", "longitude"] (with a tuple)

  • This is not valid for selecting multiple columns.

  • Pandas interprets ("latitude", "longitude") as a single tuple key, not two separate columns.

So youll get an error like:

bash
KeyError: ('latitude', 'longitude')

Rule of Thumb

  • Single brackets [] one column, returns a Series

    python
    df["latitude"]

  • Double brackets [[]] multiple columns, returns a DataFrame

    python
    df[["latitude", "longitude"]]

ChatGPT said:

Absolutely lets break this line down piece by piece so its crystal clear:

Full expression:

python
(~df_cld["ethnicity"].isin(["Non-Hispanic", "Unknown"])) &
(df_cld["ethnicity"].str.contains(
    r"Yes|Hispanic|Latino|Puerto Rican|Mexican|Cuban|Other Spanish", 
    case=False, na=False
))

This is a pandas boolean mask a Series of True/False values used to select rows in df_cld.

1 df_cld["ethnicity"].isin(["Non-Hispanic", "Unknown"])

  • .isin([...]) checks if each value in the ethnicity column matches any of the values in the list.

  • Returns a Series of True/False:

text
'Non-Hispanic' -> True
'Hispanic' -> False
'Unknown' -> True

2 ~df_cld["ethnicity"].isin([...])

  • ~ is the bitwise NOT operator in pandas.

  • It flips True False and False True.

  • So now we get True for rows that are NOT Non-Hispanic or Unknown.

text
'Non-Hispanic' -> False
'Hispanic' -> True
'Unknown' -> False

3 df_cld["ethnicity"].str.contains(r"Yes|Hispanic|Latino|Puerto Rican|Mexican|Cuban|Other Spanish", case=False, na=False)

  • .str.contains(regex) checks if each row contains any of the listed keywords.

  • r"Yes|Hispanic|Latino|Puerto Rican|Mexican|Cuban|Other Spanish" matches any row that mentions these terms (case-insensitive).

  • case=False ignores capitalization.

  • na=False treats NaN as False so it doesnt cause errors.

Example matches:

  • "Yes, Puerto Rican" True

  • "Mexican, Mexican American, Chicano" True

  • "Non-Hispanic" False

4 & (element-wise AND)

  • Combines the two conditions row by row.

  • Only rows that are:

    1. NOT already Non-Hispanic or Unknown, AND

    2. Contain one of the Hispanic-related keywords

  • will be True and get updated to "Hispanic" in the assignment.

5 Why we need both conditions

  • Without ~df_cld["ethnicity"].isin(["Non-Hispanic", "Unknown"]), rows like "No, Not Spanish/Hispanic/Latino" would match "Hispanic" because they contain the substring "Hispanic" causing overwrite.

  • Using the negation ensures that only true Hispanic rows get updated, and Non-Hispanic / Unknown rows stay untouched.

In short:

This mask selects exactly the rows that need to become Hispanic, avoiding accidental changes to Non-Hispanic or Unknown rows.

python
import snowflake.connector

# Connect to Snowflake
conn = snowflake.connector.connect(
    user="YOUR_USERNAME",
    password="YOUR_PASSWORD",
    account="YOUR_ACCOUNT",   # e.g. xy12345.ca-central-1
    warehouse="YOUR_WAREHOUSE",
    database="YOUR_DATABASE",
    schema="YOUR_SCHEMA"
)

# Create cursor
cur = conn.cursor()

# Optional: Create table if it doesn't exist
create_table_query = """
CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE DRUG_DEATHS_FORECAST (
    DATE DATE,
    FORECAST FLOAT,
    LOWER_BOUND FLOAT,
    UPPER_BOUND FLOAT
);
"""
cur.execute(create_table_query)

# Write forecast_results to Snowflake
for _, row in forecast_results.iterrows():
    cur.execute(
        """
        INSERT INTO DRUG_DEATHS_FORECAST (DATE, FORECAST, LOWER_BOUND, UPPER_BOUND)
        VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s)
        """,
        (row["date"], row["forecast"], row["lower_bound"], row["upper_bound"])
    )

conn.commit()

        temp = forecast[["ds", "yhat", "yhat_lower", "yhat_upper"]]
        temp.columns = ["date", "forecast", "lower_bound", "upper_bound"]
        temp["race"] = race
        race_forecasts.append(temp)

Prophet (and ARIMA) both have knobs you can adjust to make results more realistic, based on your datas behavior.

Goal

You want Prophet to:

  • Better fit past overdose trends

  • Capture seasonality or sudden trend changes

  • Avoid over- or under-smoothing

Step-by-Step Fine-Tuning for Prophet

Lets go through the main levers you can adjust

1 Adjust growth model

If your deaths are rising but seem to flatten recently, use logistic growth instead of linear.

python
# Set carrying capacity (maximum expected deaths)
fentanyl_df["cap"] = fentanyl_df["y"].max() * 1.2

model_fent = Prophet(
    growth="logistic"
)
model_fent.fit(fentanyl_df)

Why:
Prevents unrealistic exponential rise if your series levels off.

2 Tune trend flexibility

The parameter changepoint_prior_scale controls how flexibly Prophet fits trend changes.

ValueEffectUse when
0.0010.05smoother (less sensitive)noisy or small data
0.10.5more flexiblereal shifts (e.g., fentanyl spike in 2020)

Example:

python
model_fent = Prophet(changepoint_prior_scale=0.2)

3 Add yearly seasonality

Drug deaths often spike in certain months or seasons (e.g., summer or winter).
Since were forecasting yearly totals, we can still capture long-term cycles.

python
model_fent = Prophet(yearly_seasonality=True)

If you switch back to monthly data, Prophet can use:

python
Prophet(yearly_seasonality=True, weekly_seasonality=False, daily_seasonality=False)

4 Add extra regressors

If you have additional columns (like age, sex, or any_opioid flags), Prophet can learn from them.

Example:

python
model_fent.add_regressor('any_opioid')
model_fent.add_regressor('ethanol')
model_fent.add_regressor('methamphetamine')

Then you pass those columns in both fit and future dataframes.

Why:
This lets Prophet factor in multi-drug interactions (e.g., fentanyl + cocaine spikes).

5 Manually specify changepoints

If you know critical turning points (e.g., policy change, COVID lockdown), add them manually:

python
model_fent = Prophet(
    changepoints=["2017-07-01", "2020-03-01", "2022-01-01"],
    changepoint_prior_scale=0.2
)

6 Cross-validation for accuracy

Prophet has built-in performance testing use it to evaluate and tune parameters.

python
from prophet.diagnostics import cross_validation, performance_metrics

df_cv = cross_validation(model_fent, initial='1000 days', period='180 days', horizon='365 days')
df_p = performance_metrics(df_cv)
print(df_p[['horizon', 'mape', 'rmse']].head())

Lower mape = more accurate forecast

Then iterate:

  • Try different changepoint_prior_scale

  • Try logistic vs linear growth

  • Compare RMSE/MAPE

7 Increase data quality

Prophet can only be as good as the data. You improve accuracy by:

  • Filling small gaps (interpolate())

  • Removing outliers (e.g., single-month spikes)

  • Aggregating weekly/monthly (not daily, if too sparse)

  • Ensuring consistent reporting patterns

import pandas as pd

data = {
    "year": list(range(2012, 2025)),
    "fentanyl_cases": [14, 37, 75, 189, 482, 676, 760, 979, 1159, 1301, 1253, 1124, 762],
    "cocaine_cases": [105, 147, 127, 177, 275, 347, 345, 463, 529, 656, 684, 723, 586]
}

# --- Step 5: Forecast ---

# --- Step 6: Plot results ---
fig = model.plot(forecast)
plt.title("Fentanyl-Related Deaths Forecast (Yearly)")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Deaths")
plt.show()

# Optional: Plot components (trend, changepoints)
fig2 = model.plot_components(forecast)

You said:
In 2012 our forecast for fentanyl was 206 but prior value is 14
ChatGPT said:

Ah that huge jump is happening because Prophet is using logistic growth with a cap thats much higher than your early years.

Lets break it down:

Why the 2012 forecast is way off

  1. Logistic growth requires a cap (maximum expected value).

    • You set cap = max(y) * 1.5 762 * 1.5 1143.

    • Prophet tries to fit a smooth S-shaped curve from the first value (14) up to the cap.

    • Early years get over-smoothed upward to match the later surge.

  2. Sparse yearly data

    • With only 13 points, Prophet spreads the trend to fit the later peaks, so the first values forecast can be much higher than actual.

  3. No explicit early-year anchor

    • Prophet doesnt know that 20122015 should stay near 14189 unless you provide prior constraints or tune changepoints.

How to fix it

Option 1: Reduce the cap

Instead of 1.5 * max(y), use a smaller multiple that better reflects realistic growth:

python
fentanyl_df["cap"] = fentanyl_df["y"].max() * 1.1

Option 2: Increase trend flexibility

If you still want logistic growth, reduce the changepoint_prior_scale to avoid overshooting early years:

python
model_fent = Prophet(
    growth="logistic",
    changepoint_prior_scale=0.1,  # smoother, less aggressive trend
    yearly_seasonality=False
)

Option 3: Use linear growth instead of logistic

If your early-year counts are far from later peaks, logistic growth may overcorrect. Linear growth is often better for sparse yearly data:

python
model_fent = Prophet(
    growth="linear",
    changepoint_prior_scale=0.3,
    yearly_seasonality=False
)

This keeps early forecasts close to actuals while still modeling the surge.

Recommendation

For your 20122024 fentanyl dataset, I would suggest:

  • Use linear growth, not logistic

  • Keep changepoint_prior_scale=0.3 to capture 20162020 surge

  • Avoid setting a cap (since it distorts early-year values)

import snowflake.connector

)

# -------------------------------
# Specify target table name
table_name = 'YEARLY_OVERDOSE_FORECAST'

# Create table if it doesn't exist (optional)
create_table_query = f"""
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS {table_name} (
    YEAR DATE,
    SUBSTANCE STRING,
    FORECAST FLOAT,
    LOWER_BOUND FLOAT,
    UPPER_BOUND FLOAT,
    ACTUAL FLOAT
)
"""
conn.cursor().execute(create_table_query)

# Use write_pandas to push DataFrame
success, nchunks, nrows, _ = write_pandas(
    conn=conn,
    df=combined_df,
    table_name=table_name,
    auto_create_table=False,  # already created above
    overwrite=True            # replace old data
)

if success:
    print(f"Successfully loaded {nrows} rows into {table_name} in Snowflake.")
else:
    print("Failed to upload data.")

# Close connection
conn.close()

Notes:

3 Forecast Yearly Cases (Fentanyl & Cocaine)

python
from prophet import Prophet

def forecast_substance(df, substance, periods=3):
    df_sub = df.rename(columns={"year":"ds", f"{substance}_cases":"y"})
    df_sub["ds"] = pd.to_datetime(df_sub["ds"], format="%Y")
    df_sub["y"] = np.log1p(df_sub["y"])  # log-transform

    model = Prophet(growth="linear", changepoint_prior_scale=0.3, yearly_seasonality=False)
    model.fit(df_sub)

    future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=periods, freq="Y")
    forecast = model.predict(future)

    forecast["yhat"] = np.expm1(forecast["yhat"])
    forecast["yhat_lower"] = np.expm1(forecast["yhat_lower"])
    forecast["yhat_upper"] = np.expm1(forecast["yhat_upper"])

    # Clip negative values
    forecast["yhat"] = forecast["yhat"].clip(lower=0)
    forecast["yhat_lower"] = forecast["yhat_lower"].clip(lower=0)
    forecast["yhat_upper"] = forecast["yhat_upper"].clip(lower=0)

    forecast_df = forecast[["ds","yhat","yhat_lower","yhat_upper"]].copy()
    forecast_df.columns = ["year","forecast","lower_bound","upper_bound"]
    forecast_df["substance"] = substance.title()
    return forecast_df

# Generate forecasts
fentanyl_forecast = forecast_substance(yearly_trends, "fentanyl")
cocaine_forecast = forecast_substance(yearly_trends, "cocaine")

# Combine forecasts
yearly_forecast = pd.concat([fentanyl_forecast, cocaine_forecast], ignore_index=True)
